passages.text: H1 results saw Accelleron upgrade to its expectations for market activity in 4 of its 8 segments in Marine and Energy vs guidance given in early 2025. Accelleron market share has grown from \(40\%\) in 2022 to \(50\%\) in Marine new- builds with better share in newer dual- fuel engine designs. Retrofits and upgrades in Marine have been largely limited to larger owners of vessels with limited adoption from smaller asset owners to date. Management sees energy capacity as the key bottleneck for data center rollout in the US with the grid unlikely to address the full power capacity need (read further opportunity in DC baseload/medium- speed). Net, the company should continue to see growth drivers in equipment revenues in both Marine and Energy near- term.
Figure 1: Accelleron's updated outlook shows an improved outlook for 4 of its 8 market segments
Source: company presentation

Accelleron remains bullish on the opportunity in fuel injection with revenues expected to double to US \(150m\) by 2029 vs 2024 levels, a \(15\%\) CAGR underpinned by planned expansion capex of US \(80m\) and 150 employee adds to bolster factory capacity. Management aims to triple production at OMC2 factories as it anticipates structural growth in demand with \(30\%\) growth in relevant capacity. We see superior growth in OMT and OMC2 and the medium- speed segment underpinning continued growth in Accelleron's larger division.

FY25 revenue growth is driven by superior growth in equipment revenues at \(+35\%\) yr/yr in H1 versus service at \(+10\%\) with pockets of superior growth in Marine retrofits and upgrades and Energy builduits in balancing, emergency and prime power particularly in the US. Accelleron is enjoying pockets of super- normal growth in equipment revenues in Marine (retrofits growing \(+60\%\) yr/yr in H1) and Energy (data center revenues tripling in H2) with fuel injector revenues also high growth. In addition, service revenue growth remains strong and in- line with that of Marine peers. Revised DB forecasts call for \(+17\%\) organic rev growth in FY25 and \(+15\%\) for FY26; ahead of mgmt's longer- term guide of \(2 - 4\%\) organic revenue growth longer- term.

Limited margin expansion this year and next we have a head-wind We forecast modest margin expansion this year and next a revenue growth is mix negative with management investing in both plant and personnel to support continued growth. H1 results showed limited margin expansion due to negative mix with stronger growth in equipment revenues. New U- tariffs on Swiss goods at \(39\%\) went into effect on August \(7^{\text{th}}\) and place Accelleron at a disadvantage vs competitors should the current tariff levels hold. Historically, the company has not meaningfully participated in high- speed diesel turbocharger markets. Meaningful expansion in this market could be margin- and returns- dilutive due to competition from scaled automotive OEMs. More generic risks include forex exposure, inability to maintain margins and any major negative shifts in economic/political policy on emissions. Upside risks include further meaningful M&A and possible share buy- backs.

Macroeconomic fluctuations often account for most of the risks associated with exposures to instruments that promise to pay fixed or variable interest rates. For an investor who is long fixed- rate instruments (thus receiving these cash flows), increases in interest rates naturally lift the discount factors applied to the expected cash flows and thus cause a loss. The longer the maturity of a certain cash flow and the higher the move in the discount factor, the higher will be the loss. Upside surprises in inflation, fiscal funding needs, and FX depreciation rates are among the most common adverse macroeconomic shocks to receivers. But counterparty exposure, issuer creditworthiness, client segmentation, regulation (including changes in assets holding limits for different types of investors), changes in tax policies, currency convertibility (which may constrain currency conversion, repatriation of profits and/or liquidation of positions), and settlement issues related to local clearing houses are also important risk factors. The sensitivity of fixed- income instruments to macroeconomic shocks may be mitigated by indexing the contracted cash flows to inflation, to FX depreciation, or to specified interest rates - these are common in emerging markets. The index fixings may - by construction - lag or mis- measure the actual move in the underlying variables they are intended to track. The choice of the proper fixing (or metric) is particularly important in swaps markets, where floating coupon rates (i.e., coupons indexed to a typically short- dated interest rate reference index) are exchanged for fixed coupons. Funding in a currency that differs from the currency in which coupons are denominated carries FX risk. Options on swaps (swaptions) the risks typical to options in addition to the risks related to rates movements.
